  <static seed="254" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicMath/FractionsCalculation/AddThreeFractions40.pg">
    <statement><p>Add: <m>\displaystyle{ {{\frac{7}{10}}} + {{\frac{4}{5}}} + {{\frac{1}{3}}} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>1{\textstyle\frac{5}{6}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To add fractions with different denominators, we need to find the common denominator first. One way is to list the multiples of the largest denominator, until all <m>3</m> denominators divide into the multiple.</p>
<p>The largest denominator is <m>10</m>. We list its first few multiples:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ 10, 20, 30 }</m></p>
<p>Note that all denominators, <m>10, 5 \text{ and } 3</m> each divide into <m>30</m>.</p>
<p>The full computation is:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   \frac{7}{10} + \frac{4}{5} + \frac{1}{3}
      \amp = \frac{7 \cdot 3}{10 \cdot 3} + \frac{4 \cdot 6}{5 \cdot 6} + \frac{1 \cdot 10}{3 \cdot 10} \\
      \amp = \frac{21}{30} + \frac{24}{30} + \frac{10}{30} \\
      \amp = \frac{21+24+10}{30} \\
      \amp = \frac{55}{30} \\
      \amp = \frac{11}{6} \\
        \amp = {1{\textstyle\frac{5}{6}}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Don<rsq/>t forget to reduce the fraction <m>\frac{55}{30}</m> by dividing <m>5</m> into both the numerator and the denominator.</p>
</solution>
